Document: Curve3D
Path: godot/classes/class_curve3d.rst
Summary: This section details the properties of the Curve3D class, including bake interval, closed status, point count, and individual point attributes like position, in/out control points, and tilt.

Property Descriptions

bake_interval (float): The distance in meters between two adjacent cached points. Default: 0.2.
Method: set_bake_interval(value: float)
Method: get_bake_interval()
Changing this value forces the cache to be recomputed the next time the get_baked_points() or get_baked_length() function is called. The smaller the distance, the more points in the cache and the more memory it will consume, so use with care.

closed (bool): If true, and the curve has more than 2 control points, the last point and the first one will be connected in a loop. Default: false.
Method: set_closed(value: bool)
Method: is_closed()

point_count (int): The number of points describing the curve. Default: 0.
Method: set_point_count(value: int)
Method: get_point_count()

point_{index}/in (Vector3): The position of the control point leading to the vertex at `index`. Default: Vector3(0, 0, 0).
Note: `index` is a value in the `0 .. point_count - 1` range.

point_{index}/out (Vector3): The position of the control point leading out of the vertex at `index`. Default: Vector3(0, 0, 0).
Note: `index` is a value in the `0 .. point_count - 1` range.

point_{index}/position (Vector3): The position of for the vertex at `index`. Default: Vector3(0, 0, 0).
Note: `index` is a value in the `0 .. point_count - 1` range.

point_{index}/tilt (float): The tilt angle in radians for the point at `index`. Default: 0.0.
Note: `index` is a value in the `0 .. point_count - 1` range.

up_vector_enabled (bool): If true, the curve will bake up vectors used for orientation. Default: true.
Method: set_up_vector_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_up_vector_enabled()
This is used when PathFollow3D.rotation_mode is set to PathFollow3D.ROTATION_ORIENTED. Changing it forces the cache to be recomputed.
---CHUNK---
Document: Curve3D
Path: godot/classes/class_curve3d.rst
Summary: This section details methods for adding and removing points, retrieving baked curve data, and accessing individual point properties like position, control points, and tilt.

Method: add_point(position: Vector3, in: Vector3 = Vector3(0, 0, 0), out: Vector3 = Vector3(0, 0, 0), index: int = -1) → void
Adds a point with the specified `position` relative to the curve's own position, with control points `in` and `out`. Appends the new point at the end of the point list. If `index` is given, the new point is inserted before the existing point identified by index `index`. Every existing point starting from `index` is shifted further down the list of points. The index must be greater than or equal to `0` and must not exceed the number of existing points in the line. See point_count.

Method: clear_points() → void
Removes all points from the curve.

Method: get_baked_length() → float
Returns the total length of the curve, based on the cached points. Given enough density (see bake_interval), it should be approximate enough.

Method: get_baked_points() → PackedVector3Array
Returns the cache of points as a PackedVector3Array.

Method: get_baked_tilts() → PackedFloat32Array
Returns the cache of tilts as a PackedFloat32Array.

Method: get_baked_up_vectors() → PackedVector3Array
Returns the cache of up vectors as a PackedVector3Array. If up_vector_enabled is `false`, the cache will be empty.

Method: get_closest_offset(to_point: Vector3) → float
Returns the closest offset to `to_point`. This offset is meant to be used in sample_baked() or sample_baked_up_vector(). `to_point` must be in this curve's local space.

Method: get_closest_point(to_point: Vector3) → Vector3
Returns the closest point on baked segments (in curve's local space) to `to_point`. `to_point` must be in this curve's local space.

Method: get_point_in(idx: int) → Vector3
Returns the position of the control point leading to the vertex `idx`. The returned position is relative to the vertex `idx`. If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns `(0, 0, 0)`.

Method: get_point_out(idx: int) → Vector3
Returns the position of the control point leading out of the vertex `idx`. The returned position is relative to the vertex `idx`. If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns `(0, 0, 0)`.

Method: get_point_position(idx: int) → Vector3
Returns the position of the vertex `idx`. If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns `(0, 0, 0)`.

Method: get_point_tilt(idx: int) → float
Returns the tilt angle in radians for the point `idx`. If the index is out of bounds, the function sends an error to the console, and returns `0`.

Method: remove_point(idx: int) → void
Deletes the point `idx` from the curve. Sends an error to the console if `idx` is out of bounds.